      <div class="faq-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">FAQ</div>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the FICA tax rate for 2026?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The FICA tax rate for 2026 is 7.65% for employees: 6.2% for Social Security on wages up to the projected wage base of approximately $180,400, and 1.45% for Medicare on all wages. Employers match the same 7.65%. Self-employed individuals pay the full 15.3% combined rate.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the 2026 Social Security wage base?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The official 2026 Social Security wage base has not been announced. Based on recent wage growth trends, it is projected at approximately $180,400, up from $176,100 in 2025. The SSA typically announces the official figure in October each year.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Does Medicare tax have a wage cap in 2026?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. The 1.45% Medicare tax applies to all wages with no ceiling. High earners also pay an additional 0.9% Medicare surtax on wages above $200,000 (single filers) or $250,000 (married filing jointly). Employers do not match the additional 0.9%.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What happens when I hit the Social Security wage base?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Once your year-to-date wages exceed the wage base (approximately $180,400 for 2026), Social Security withholding stops for the remainder of the year. Your employer is responsible for tracking this. Medicare withholding continues on all wages with no cap. You will notice a larger net paycheck in months after you hit the cap.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Can I deduct FICA taxes?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">W-2 employees cannot deduct their share of FICA taxes. Self-employed individuals can deduct half of their self-employment tax (the equivalent of the employer share) as an above-the-line adjustment to income on Form 1040 Schedule 1. This reduces AGI but does not reduce SE tax itself.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
